b'<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>\r\n<!DOCTYPE workbook_page PUBLIC "-//Carnegie Mellon University//DTD Workbook Page MathML 3.8//EN" "http://oli.web.cmu.edu/dtd/oli_workbook_page_mathml_3_8.dtd">\r\n<workbook_page xmlns:bib="http://bibtexml.sf.net/"\r\n\txmlns:cmd="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/content/metadata/2.1/"\r\n\txmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" xmlns:pref="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/preferences/"\r\n\txmlns:theme="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/presentation/"\r\n\txmlns:wb="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/activity/workbook/" id="p7_ideal_gas">\r\n\t<head>\r\n\t\t<title>The Ideal Gas Law</title>\r\n\t\t<objref idref="gas_laws"/>\r\n\t</head>\r\n\t<body>\r\n\t\t<p id="f84290b4e4f24d2984dbf26f81264b6a">To this point, four separate laws have been\r\n\t\t\tdiscussed that relate pressure, volume, temperature, and the number of moles of the\r\n\t\t\tgas:</p>\r\n\t\t<ul id="dd1d54d7d9504f4382d9c55a5769bd4c">\r\n\t\t\t<li>Boyle\xe2\x80\x99s law:\r\n\t\t\t\t$$PV=k\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\mathrm{at}\\;\\mathrm{constant}\\;T\\;\\mathrm{and}\\;n$$</li>\r\n\t\t\t<li>Gay-Lussac&apos;s law: $$\\frac\r\n\t\t\t\tPT\\;=\\;k\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\mathrm{at}\\;\\mathrm{constant}\\;V\\;\\mathrm{and}\\;n$$</li>\r\n\t\t\t<li>Charles\xe2\x80\x99s law: $$\\frac\r\n\t\t\t\tVT\\;=\\;k\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\mathrm{at}\\;\\mathrm{constant}\\;P\\;\\mathrm{and}\\;n$$</li>\r\n\t\t\t<li>Avogadro\xe2\x80\x99s law: $$\\frac\r\n\t\t\t\tVn\\;=\\;k\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\mathrm{at}\\;\\mathrm{constant}\\;P\\;\\mathrm{and}\\;T$$</li>\r\n\t\t</ul>\r\n\t\t<p id="d50eafe89ef242758c8b810d10139897">Combining these four laws yields the ideal gas\r\n\t\t\tlaw.</p>\r\n\t\t<image src="../../../webcontent/green_line.png"></image>\r\n\t\t<dl>\r\n\t\t\t<dt><em>The Ideal Gas Law</em></dt>\r\n\t\t\t<dd>\r\n\t\t\t\t<p>The <extra><anchor>ideal gas law</anchor><meaning><material><p>relation between the pressure, volume, amount, and temperature of a gas under conditions derived by combination of the simple gas laws</p></material></meaning></extra> shows the relation between the pressure, volume, temperature,\r\n\t\t\t\t\tand number of moles of a gas:</p>\r\n\t\t\t\t<formula>$$PV\\;=\\;nRT$$</formula>\r\n\t\t\t\t<p> where <em style="italic">P</em> is the pressure of a gas, <em style="italic"\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t>V</em> is its volume, <em style="italic">n</em> is the number of moles of\r\n\t\t\t\t\tthe gas, <em style="italic">T</em> is its temperature on the kelvin scale, and\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<em style="italic">R</em> is a constant called the ideal gas constant or the\r\n\t\t\t\t\tuniversal gas constant. The units used to express pressure, volume, and\r\n\t\t\t\t\ttemperature will determine the proper form of the gas constant as required by\r\n\t\t\t\t\tdimensional analysis, the most commonly encountered values being 0.08206 L atm\r\n\t\t\t\t\tmol <sup>\xe2\x80\x931</sup> K <sup>\xe2\x80\x931</sup> and 8.314 kPa L mol <sup>\xe2\x80\x931</sup> K\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<sup>\xe2\x80\x931</sup> . </p>\r\n\t\t\t</dd>\r\n\t\t</dl>\r\n\t\t<image src="../../../webcontent/green_line.png"></image>\r\n\t\t<p id="c4d975a71506487cae82b22ef17ae63c"> Gases whose properties of <em style="italic"\r\n\t\t\t\t>P</em> , <em style="italic">V</em> , and <em style="italic">T</em> are accurately\r\n\t\t\tdescribed by the ideal gas law (or the other gas laws) are said to exhibit ideal\r\n\t\t\tbehavior or to approximate the traits of an ideal gas. An ideal gas is a hypothetical\r\n\t\t\tconstruct that may be used along with kinetic molecular theory to effectively explain\r\n\t\t\tthe gas laws as will be described later in this unit. Although all the calculations\r\n\t\t\tpresented in this module assume ideal behavior, this assumption is only reasonable for\r\n\t\t\tgases under conditions of relatively low pressure and high temperature. In the final\r\n\t\t\tmodule of this unit, a modified gas law will be introduced that accounts for the\r\n\t\t\tnon-ideal behavior observed for many gases at relatively high pressures and low\r\n\t\t\ttemperatures. </p>\r\n\t\t<p id="d4f57044f8524e938c51d8ae356ad5d2"> The ideal gas equation contains five terms, the\r\n\t\t\t<extra><anchor>ideal gas constant</anchor><meaning><material><p>constant derived from the ideal gas equation R = 0.08206 L atm mol<sup>\xe2\x80\x931</sup> K<sup>\xe2\x80\x931</sup> or 8.314 L kPa mol<sup>\xe2\x80\x931</sup> K<sup>\xe2\x80\x931</sup></p></material></meaning></extra>, <em style="italic">R</em> , and the variable properties <em\r\n\t\t\t\tstyle="italic">P</em> , <em style="italic">V</em> , <em style="italic">n</em> , and\r\n\t\t\t\t<em style="italic">T</em> . Specifying any four of these terms will permit use of\r\n\t\t\tthe ideal gas law to calculate the fifth term as demonstrated in the following examples. </p>\r\n\t\t<wb:inline idref="dnd_pvnrt_question" purpose="learnbydoing"></wb:inline>\r\n\t\t\r\n\t\t<wb:inline idref="ideal_lbd2bfbe7a04157d455badd736eabe66fc30" purpose="learnbydoing"/>\r\n\t\t\r\n\t\t<wb:inline idref="ideal_digte34405f2acd64389b7ce76ab2976c37b" purpose="didigetthis"></wb:inline>\r\n\t\t<p id="a5eea0dba107403391c3fd9e1ee2ed41"/>\r\n\t\t<p id="ca1233d4a3ca4fa2ac78e05dab34d67a"/>\r\n\t\t\r\n\t\t<image src="../../../webcontent/green_line.png"></image>\r\n\t\t<dl>\r\n\t\t\t<dt><em>The Combined Gas Law</em></dt>\r\n\t\t\t<dd>\r\n\t\t\t\t<p>If the number of moles of an ideal gas are kept constant under two different sets\r\n\t\t\t\t\tof conditions, a useful mathematical relationship called the combined gas law is\r\n\t\t\t\t\tobtained:</p>\r\n\t\t\t\t<formula>$$\\frac{P_1V_1}{T_1}\\;=\\;\\frac{\\;P_2V_2}{T_2}$$</formula>\r\n\t\t\t\t<p> using units of atm, L, and K. Both sets of conditions are equal to the product\r\n\t\t\t\t\tof <em style="italic">n</em> \xc3\x97 <em style="italic">R</em> (where <em\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\tstyle="italic">n</em> = the number of moles of the gas and R is the ideal\r\n\t\t\t\t\tgas law constant). </p>\r\n\t\t\t</dd>\r\n\t\t</dl>\r\n\t\t<image src="../../../webcontent/green_line.png"></image>\r\n\t\t<example id="d9cdb42e63f04c1087fff46e2f43bd36">\r\n\t\t\t<title/>\r\n\t\t\t<p id="fd7a080e0f9a47f6809111ece27983f8">When filled with air, a typical scuba tank with\r\n\t\t\t\ta volume of 13.2 L has a pressure of 153 atm. If the water temperature is 27 \xc2\xb0C, how\r\n\t\t\t\tmany liters of air will such a tank provide to a diver\xe2\x80\x99s lungs at a depth of\r\n\t\t\t\tapproximately 70 feet in the ocean where the pressure is 3.13 atm?</p>\r\n\t\t\t<image id="bd473fb9be574955831d2ad1d2a4c129" src="../webcontent/scuba_diver.png"\r\n\t\t\t\talt="This photograph shows a scuba diver underwater with a tank on their back and bubbles ascending from the breathing apparatus." style="inline" vertical-align="middle" width="400">\r\n\t\t\t\t<caption/>\r\n\t\t\t\t<popout enable="false"/>\r\n\t\t\t</image>\r\n\t\t\t<p id="c465c90ddc23452293c53e201bb0615f">Letting 1 represent the air in the scuba tank\r\n\t\t\t\tand 2 represent the air in the lungs, and noting that body temperature (the\r\n\t\t\t\ttemperature the air will be in the lungs) is 37 \xc2\xb0C, we can identify the\r\n\t\t\t\tvariables as:</p>\r\n\t\t\t<formula id="d573df11613c44e8ae08db35a6accb11"\r\n\t\t\t\t>$$\\begin{array}{l}P_1\\;=\\;153\\;\\mathrm{atm}\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;P_2\\;=\\;3.13\\;\\mathrm{atm}\\\\V_1\\;=\\;13.2\\;\\mathrm\r\n\t\t\t\tL\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;V_2\\;=\\;?\\\\T_1\\;=\\;300\\;\\mathrm\r\n\t\t\t\tK\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;T_2\\;=\\;310\\;\\mathrm\r\n\t\t\t\tK\\end{array}$$</formula>\r\n\t\t\t<p id="a2b94d131da441028e88db3310c6365c">Plug in variables and solve for the\r\n\t\t\t\tunknown.</p>\r\n\t\t\t<formula id="ff99f047890241ddb9acf1fdbf04b5d2"\r\n\t\t\t\t>$$\\frac{P_1V_1}{T_1}\\;=\\;\\frac{\\;P_2V_2}{T_2}$$</formula>\r\n\t\t\t<formula id="ee3d989b1ee940678ab48f90b69ad6e4">$$\\frac{(153\\;\\mathrm{atm})(13.2\\;\\mathrm\r\n\t\t\t\tL)}{(300\\;\\mathrm K)}\\;=\\;\\frac{(3.13\\;\\mathrm{atm})(V_2)}{(310\\;\\mathrm\r\n\t\t\t\tK)}$$</formula>\r\n\t\t\t<formula id="b0a06e77052343bb9d92cd37e957b882"\r\n\t\t\t\t>$$\\require{cancel}V_2\\;=\\frac{\\;(153\\;\\cancel{\\mathrm{atm}})\\;(13.2\\;\\mathrm\r\n\t\t\t\tL)\\;(310\\cancel{\\;\\mathrm K})}{(300\\;\\cancel{\\mathrm\r\n\t\t\t\tK})\\;(3.13\\;\\cancel{\\mathrm{atm}})\\;}=\\;667\\;\\mathrm L$$</formula>\r\n\t\t</example>\r\n\t\t<wb:inline idref="dnd_combined_question" purpose="learnbydoing"></wb:inline>\r\n\t\t\t\r\n\t\t<wb:inline idref="ideal_digt2af917b59530d49b79ff4e57543a9b022" purpose="didigetthis"/>\r\n\t\t\r\n\t\t<p id="be64b88388c14dea94b9b181082c4600"> Adapted from <link\r\n\t\t\t\thref="https://cnx.org/contents/havxkyvS@9.422:b39avmGq@29/Preface" target="self"\r\n\t\t\t\tinternal="false">Openstax Chemistry</link> under <link\r\n\t\t\t\thref="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/" target="self" internal="false"\r\n\t\t\t\t>Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 License.</link>\r\n\t\t</p>\r\n\t\t<p id="dc86c2d5cb4c4b2faa13ba5e269445b6"> Download for free at <link\r\n\t\t\t\thref="http://cnx.org/contents/85abf193-2bd2-4908-8563-90b8a7ac8df6@9.312"\r\n\t\t\t\ttarget="self" internal="false"\r\n\t\t\t\t>http://cnx.org/contents/85abf193-2bd2-4908-8563-90b8a7ac8df6@9.312.</link>\r\n\t\t</p>\r\n\t</body>\r\n</workbook_page>\r\n'